IRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecilia Bisset was born about 1250, in Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland, her father, John Bisset Lord of Lovat, was 61 and her mother, Ermengarde Durward, was 18. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with William Fenton. She died about 1320, in Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland, at the age of 72."},"et":{"Abt 1250–Abt 1320":"umbes 1250–umbes 1320","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1248–1348":"1248–1348","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1252–Male":"1252–Surnud","1240–1316":"1240–1316","1270–1325":"1270–1325","1270–1336":"1270–1336","1190–1259":"1190–1259","1233–Female":"1233–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1316":"umbes 1316","1316":"1316","1348":"1348","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1259":"1259","1336":"1336","1325":"1325","1248":"1248","1235":"1235","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1233":"1233","1320":"1320","Clan Fenton, East Lo